  "body": " Daily Prep 1.2 - The Notion of a Limit   Overview  We will now begin to investigate the idea of the limit of a function at a given input value. Limits are important in calculus for many reasons, but perhaps most important for how they allow us to formally connect instantaneous velocity to average velocity.  This section covers the following concepts: Definition and notation of limits. Graphical interpretation, table of values, algebraic computation. Indeterminate form of type .    Basic learning objectives  These are the tasks you should be able to perform with reasonable fluency when you arrive at our next class meeting. Important new vocabulary words are indicated in italics .    State the two related formulas for the average velocity of an object with position function on an interval and on the interval .    Interpret the meaning of notation such as  . Use limit notation.    Use computations of average velocity to determine instantaneous velocity.    Provide examples (both graphically and numerically) of functions that do not have a limit at a specific value.    Estimate\/hypothesize the limit of a function at a point on a graph (or determine that it does not exist).      To prepare for class  Complete all actions listed below. Respond to the questions highlighted with Submit .  A single .pdf should be uploaded to D2L Brightspace. See the syllabus for grading rubric. Strive to use valid notation and correct mathematical language and syntax. All answers should be briefly justified, whether justification is specifically requested or not.     Read the beginning of section 1.2 (up until the preview activity).    [Submit] Do Preview Activity 1.2.1.     Read  section 1.2.1 : The Notion of Limit.     Watch this video on evaluating limits from the graph of a function: Limits (6:01) .    [Submit] Do Example 1.2.4(a) in the textbook (without reading the solution), using the graph of the function: Use  Desmos  to graph (you define by typing , and you can click and drag points on the graph to see the precise coordinates). Finally, read the solution. Is the graph that Desmos produces accurate? Explain. Produce a screen capture of your work in doing Example 1.2.4(a) using Desmos .     Watch this video on evaluating limits using graphing tools ( GeoGebra ): Limits of Functions Using Graphing Tools (6:26) .    [Submit] Redo Example 1.2.4(a) from the textbook using  GeoGebra  rather than Desmos . Produce a screen capture of your work in doing Example 1.2.4(a) using GeoGebra .     Do the following exercises.     Are the following statements about true or false? Why?        is in the domain of      exists     is equal to        Sketch the graph of an example of a function that satisfies all of the following: , , , , and .      For the function whose graph is given, state the value of each quantity, if it exists. If it does not exist, explain why.                                                                         After class  Solidifying the concepts discussed in class through practice is necessary to build your skills. Mathematics is not a spectator sport!     Watch the following video, which shows how to estimate a limit from a table of function values: Limits of Functions Using Tables (5:57) .    Prompt Copilot I want to better understand limits in calculus. Why cant I just plug in values?    Prompt Copilot Im in my first week of learning calculus. What is this thing called an indeterminant form?     Do  Exercises 1-4 in section 1.2.4 of the textbook . These give you instantaneous feedback.     Read the sections 1.2.2 and the summary in 1.2.3 .     Watch the following video on using spreadsheets to investigate limits: Limits of Functions Using Spreadsheets (5:37) .     Redo Example 1.2.4(a) in the textbook (without reading the solution), using a spreadsheet. Then, do Example 1.2.4(b) using a spreadsheet.     Do  Exercises 5-8 in section 1.2.4 .     Start working on the MOMwork (MyOpenMath) assignment for this section.      Advanced learning objectives  In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able to perform after class, with practice:    Estimate the limit of a function at a point using the algebraic formula (or determine that it does not exist). This includes indeterminate forms of type .    Compute instantaneous velocities using both formulas.    Demonstrate instantaneous velocity graphically on a position graph.    Explain how instantaneous velocity is thought of as a limit of average velocities.      Additional suggestions     Watch the following video which gives an introduction to the concept of limits: Introduction to the Concept of Limits (9:29) .     Watch the following video, which shows how to evaluate certain limits when the graph of the function is known: Evaluating Limits Using a Graph (9:51) .      Answers       True; the function is defined (as per black dot)    True; the limits from the left and the right are the same    True; however, these limits do not equal        Answer will vary.   One possible graph.                          does not exist               does not exist               does not exist          does not exist       "
